“I’m taking it upon myself, and challenging you as well, to skip the diet-focused resolution. Statistically, diets don’t ever pan out the way you want them to. Why not accrue a different positive habit instead of setting yourself up for failure with virtually impossible goals?”

This ⬆️ is a quote from my 2017 blog post about resolutions, and it was the start of my long journey towards peace with food, movement, and my body. And it’s still all relevant now, 6 years later! 

So many people will embark on weight loss again and again, never seeing long term results. So can we just wave a white flag to our bodies? Surrender to their softness and spend our energy on things that matter? Things that are possible? Things that make our lives better?

I think we can! So here are some ideas, and I’d love to hear yours too 🏳️🏳️🏳️

Had to share some fat joy today because damn, it’s been a hard month for fat folks. 

It’s always harder for us, and January is the worst month of all, but there are some mega shifts happening in the fat community and in society at large. It just feels like the hits keep coming. So I’m going to share some things to keep in mind, to stop yourself from spiraling into self loathing, during this weird and sad time. 

No weight loss pill or procedure will give you long term results and they both come with a slew of negative health outcomes. 

You can respect and care for your body without using weight or size as a metric. 

If your fat faves are disappointing you, it’s okay to unfollow. 

Everyone has bodily autonomy- but some choices are fatphobic. Some choices are not aligned with body liberation. 

People of all sizes have health challenges. There is no health challenge that is solely reserved for fat bodies. 

No child should be given weight loss pills or weight loss surgery. Comparing that to gender affirming care is transphobic and just silly. 

Fat actors should be in fat roles. Fat suits are shameful. 

Health has no moral value. You are worthy of dignity and respect at any size, any ability. So many factors go into your size and health, and health cannot be determined on sight. 

😮‍💨 Sending you all love and strength to continue choosing yourself and your happiness. This little corner of the internet will always be a safer space, a body liberation space. Promise ♥️

#fatliberation #bodyliberation #fatjoy #healthisnotasize #fatandhappy #fatandfree

If I could say anything to 12-year-old me, who was getting her first period on a sweaty leg press machine, surrounded by middle-age women who hate themselves, it would be this:

Your body is not a problem.

I remember when my mom took me to sign us both up for a womens-only circuit gym. When asked why she was joining, she said “I want to feel better. I want to look better.” 

Look better, aka look thinner. Because being fat meant looking bad, and I was already wearing pants from the plus size womens section. 

This moment, along with a hundred other tiny moments I can’t even remember, led me to disordered eating in the 7th grade, and an unhealthy relationship with food, movement, and my body for years to come. 

If I didn’t find the fat posi corner of the internet, I don’t know where I’d be right now. And I had this realization: kids aren’t getting positive messages about their bodies or abilities from anywhere. Some parents take up the torch (love y’all!) but there are no assemblies or after school specials about body kindness, respect, and the deep importance of full-body wellbeing. 

And it’s really GETTING to me. The bullshit medical recommendations for fat kids is ENRAGING me. After listening to the @maintenancephase  ep about the topic, I can’t stop thinking about it. So if anyone wants to team up with me to create a badass presentation for kids on how to lead with self-compassion and kindness to their bodies, the DMs are open ♥️

Hey you. 

Did you know that your light shines on everyone around you?

Even in the quiet moments, you are beaming. Even on the days when you’re barely hanging on, we can see your glow. 

Embers waiting to ignite. 

Your sadness, spiraling, cavernous moments cannot snuff out your light. I hope that in moments when you can’t see, someone else can be your eyes. 

Today, I’ll be your eyes. 

I see how hard you’re trying. I see you kindling your fire. I see you warming your hands and waiting on the storm to pass. 

You are a precious light in this world, as a roaring fire or a smoldering match. My hand will block the wind. And your light will guide us home.

A 5-minute ab workout is an ab workout 

A 10 minute walk is a walk

One set of reps is a lifting session 

I had so many arbitrary rules for exercise. And all it did was keep me from moving my body! Because I didn’t have enough time, energy, or motivation. 

But the thing is, if you do 5 minutes of core exercises a day, you’ll have a stronger core in 30 days. There is no magic threshold in which movement has a positive impact. Every minute, every activation of a muscle, has a positive impact.

Maybe I’ve been watching too much House MD, or maybe I’m getting hyped to meet with a new doctor next month but I am ready to FIGHT THE SYSTEM of fatphobic healthcare. 

I’m tired and angry that I’ve felt so helpless and uncomfortable with doctors. I’m taking control of my healthcare! I’m not leaving it up to chance. Here’s my plan:

Create a document noting what I expect from my doctor including: weight neutral care, no weight loss talk, no unnecessary tests based on my size. I’ll also be specific about what I need addressed in this appointment. AND I might even print out some info about lipedema and weight-neutral care. Then I’ll give that document to nurse when I check in, to give to the doctor before she sees me. 

I’m not even going to let them TRY a blood pressure machine on my arms because it never works. And I’ll decline to be weighed. Believe me, “Note in my chart that you’re refusing that test” will be thrown around if needed. 

Recently I’ve been noticing so many moments in life where I’m uncomfortable and I freeze or fawn and I’m just done taking anyone’s shit. I don’t care if I seem rude or annoying. I deserve the same level of care and respect as anyone else. We all do. 

How do you prep for a doctors appointment? Any tips or resources? Share in the comments! 👩‍⚕️

CW: Disordered eating behaviors 

You’ve probably struggled with disordered eating at some point in your life. Every time you checked a calorie count, ignored a hunger cue, or binged on food after everyone has gone to bed, you were simply not eating the way most humans are meant to: intuitively. 

It’s not your fault, of course. The culture made us this way, gaslighting us into thinking we’re uncontrollable monsters instead of what we really are: hungry. 

There’s SO many resources for intuitive eating/healing your relationship with food. I thought I had done ALL my work around food, until I met my partner, whose mindset around eating was so pleasure-based. I realized I had healed myself to the point where I could eat without shame or guilt- but I was never eating for pleasure. 

The last 3 years have been an incredible journey for me as I’ve learned to become a damn good cook and experienced cuisines from all over the world. Growing up in a small town and being afraid of food my whole life, I had no idea I was missing so much. 

Wherever you are on your journey, I hope you can take time in the next few days to prioritize eating for pleasure. Take yourself out. Make your favorite meal from childhood. Bake something new and eat it with friends. And enjoy every bite!
